butcher /ˈbʊtʃə/

(butchering,butchered,butchers) 

1. N-COUNT A butcher is a shopkeeper who cuts up and sells meat. Some butchers also kill animals for meat and make foods such as sausages and meat pies. 屠夫; 肉商 

2. N-COUNT A butcher or a butcher's is a shop where meat is sold. 肉铺 [英国英语] 

例： He worked in a butcher's. 他在肉铺工作。 

3. V-T To butcher an animal means to kill it and cut it up for meat. 宰杀 

例： Pigs were butchered, hams were hung to dry from the ceiling. 猪被宰杀了，火腿吊在屋顶下风干。 

4. V-T You can say that someone has butchered people when they have killed a lot of people in a very cruel way, and you want to express your horror and disgust. 屠杀 [表不满] 

例： ...rebels who butchered eight tourists in Bwindi national park. …在布文迪国家公园屠杀了8名游客的叛乱分子。

